  {
    "objectID": "CV.html#field-lab-and-research-experience",
    "href": "CV.html#field-lab-and-research-experience",
    "title": "CV",
    "section": "FIELD, LAB, AND RESEARCH EXPERIENCE",
    "text": "FIELD, LAB, AND RESEARCH EXPERIENCE\nUniversity of Oregon Archaeobotany Lab, Eugene, Oregon | October 2025 - June 2026\nSupervisor: Dr. Gyoung-Ah Lee\nVolunteered in this lab to gain experience with starch and microbotanical analysis. Learned how to complete steps of starch analysis on archaeological ceramics, including ceramics from Project P’Teah to contribute to our understanding of Prasat Baset.\nStudent Research Assistant, Project P’Teah, Battambang, Cambodia | June 2024 - June 2026\nSupervisor: Dr. Alison Carter\nJoined Project P’Teah as a student research assistant for five weeks in Battambang, Cambodia (specifically focusing on the temple, Prasat Baset). Duties with data collection, cataloging, preliminary analysis, photography, and measurements. Gained knowledge regarding ceramics in Cambodia and ceramic identification.\nUniversity of Oregon Island and Coastal Archaeology Lab, Eugene, Oregon | January 2024 - June 2024\nSupervisor: Dr. Scott Fitzpatrick\nDuties included cataloging artifacts, maintained a database, and organized the collections spanning 25 years of archaeological work. Participated in a poster session at the Undergraduate Research Symposium at the University of Oregon regarding the collections of shells, bones, and other materials."
  },
  {
    "objectID": "CV.html#job-experience",
    "href": "CV.html#job-experience",
    "title": "CV",
    "section": "JOB EXPERIENCE",
    "text": "JOB EXPERIENCE\nTour Guide, University of Oregon Clark Honors College, Eugene, Oregon | January 2023- June 2026\nDuties include leading tours and occasionally presenting in larger settings. Increased confidence regarding public speaking and sharing information effectively. Presented in larger settings of up to 100 people at Duck Days events for prospective Clark Honors College students.\nArchaeology Intern, WSP, Riverside, CA | June 2025- August 2025\nJoined WSP to assist with Cultural Resource Management team in Southern California. Learned CRM processes and legal implications of CRM. Increased understanding of application of laws and procedures expected nationally and statewide in California. Assisted with tribal consultation.\nBarista, Ovation Coffee and Tea, Portland, Oregon | June 2022 - August 2023\nBegan with little coffee experience, worked up to being a barista and could make the wide range of drinks on the menu. Gained experience with customer service, time management, and teamwork."
  },
  {
    "objectID": "CV.html#relevant-coursework",
    "href": "CV.html#relevant-coursework",
    "title": "CV",
    "section": "RELEVANT COURSEWORK",
    "text": "RELEVANT COURSEWORK\nGIS I, GIS II, Advanced GIS with Python, Geographic Data Analysis, Remote Sensing I, Remote Sensing II, Web Mapping, Spatial Demography, Geographic Data Analysis, Changing Landscapes, Statistics, Statistical Analysis for Biological Anthropology, Introduction to Python, Protein Wars, Nutritional Anthropology, Food in World History, Food Science and Sustainability, Health, Food, and Culture, Ancient Psychoactive Substances, Southeast Asian Archaeology."
  },
  {
    "objectID": "CV.html#additional-experience",
    "href": "CV.html#additional-experience",
    "title": "CV",
    "section": "ADDITIONAL EXPERIENCE",
    "text": "ADDITIONAL EXPERIENCE\n2024 Food, Culture, and Sustainability, University of Oregon, Siena, Italy\nTook four courses at the University of Oregon center in Siena, Italy. Explored farming, food, and sustainability with an emphasis on Italian culture throughout the 12-week long program.\n2023-2024 Emerging Leadership Project, University of Oregon, Eugene, Oregon\nA year-long program involving weekly meetings and volunteer hours. Gained knowledge and skills to work effectively within teams to contribute my unique leadership skills and style."
  },
